Users are able to choose between running the GUI and using the standard
 text-based shell interface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Maintanibility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The software can be extended to support new functionality such as custom
 modules, user-specified diagnostics, logging and outputs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The software is documented for readability.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The public interfaces exposed by the software’s underlying code are documented
 for future development.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
All attributes and methods of the non-public implementation within the software’
s underlying code are commented.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The formatting of the software’s underlying code conforms to industry-standard
 best practices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The naming conventions present in the software’s underlying code conforms
 to industry-standard best practices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
System Evolution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Future versions will support access to more experiment variables and greater
 parallelization of modules.
 The system can be expanded in the future to automatically control distribution
 of parallel resources and computations.
 As AMUSE grows, the system should be able to support new types of modules
 and computations so that it is still a useful framework.
 Visualization tools can be added to the framework so that users can see
 a graphical representation of their output data.
\end_layout

